Part 1

The bulldozer was yellow, with a dented steel bucket that had *Escorts* painted in peeling red letters on the side. It sat parked near the shelter's outer gate for three days before it actually started working. 

The driver spent the first two days sleeping in the cabin, his bare legs dangling out of the open door, his dirty shirt thrown over the black steering wheel to block the afternoon sun.

On the third morning, the municipal junior engineer arrived in a green jeep. He didn't bother to get down. 

He simply waved a damp blue paper toward Sarita, who was standing near the well holding a plastic bucket. "Road widening," he shouted over the loud rumble of the jeep's engine. "Clear the rooms by twelve o'clock."

"We have fourteen patients in there," Sarita said, her voice steady. "Three of them cannot walk."

"The demolition order was signed in March, sister," the engineer said, checking his watch. "The contractor is paying daily rent on the machine. Twelve o'clock is the hard deadline."

He turned the jeep around, the tyres throwing up a thick cloud of dust. The dust settled on the nearby drumstick trees, turning the green leaves a dull, powdery grey.

---

Vikram had walked to the local post office to call Rohan. He dialled the office number twice from the coin-box phone, his fingers smelling of iron. 

Both times, the receptionist's voice had come through the heavy static of the long-distance line, polite and completely unyielding.

"Ahuja saab is in a board meeting. Leave a message."

"Tell him it's Vikram."

"Yes, sir. I have noted it in the ledger," she said, her voice remote.

He didn't call a third time. He hung up the black receiver, took his change, and walked back to the shelter.

At eleven-thirty, the steel bucket of the yellow bulldozer touched the outer courtyard wall. There was a low, grating sound of dry mortar giving way as the bricks crumbled. 

Ananya stood near the kitchen door. She was holding her wooden horse and the school notebook with the white chalk drawings. 

She wasn't crying. She looked at the heavy yellow machine with the same unblinking, serious curiosity she had used for the maths equations.

"It is very loud," she said, looking up at Vikram.

"Yes," Vikram said.

"Will they break the well too?"

"Yes."

She nodded. She walked to his side, her small hand finding the side pocket of his faded cotton shirt and holding onto the fabric. "Where will we sleep tonight?"

"Kolkata," Vikram said.

---

The train was the Howrah Express. They had three third-class compartments, the tickets bought with the last eight thousand rupees Sarita had kept in the shelter's steel tin box. 

The patients sat near the windows, their thin, fever-flushed faces drawing the immediate attention of the vendors selling tea and peanuts at every station. 

An old woman with a severe cough kept her face covered with her cotton saree border. A passenger from the middle berth looked down, saw her thin, scarred wrists, and quietly moved his leather luggage to the upper rack. 

He didn't say a word. Neither did Sarita. 

She sat opposite Vikram, her forehead pressed against the cold iron bars of the window. The fever had returned. 

Her skin was hot to the touch, dry and paper-thin in the afternoon heat. "The house belongs to my late husband's uncle," she said. Her voice was thin, dry like the warm breeze blowing through the train window. "He died in ninety-two. The sons went to Delhi. Nobody has lived there for twenty years."

"Is there a well?" Vikram asked.

"A municipal tap," she said. "In the corner of the courtyard. And three big neem trees. The leaves are good for cooling the skin."

She closed her eyes. "It is in Bagbazar. Near the river. The wind smells of wet jute and river mud."

Vikram looked out at the passing landscape. The green paddy fields of Odisha were slowly giving way to the grey marshlands and brick kilns of Bengal. 

The iron wheels of the train kept up their rhythmic, metallic clank. 

*Fourteen hundred.* 

*Fourteen hundred.* 

*Fourteen hundred.* 

The number didn't have the same sound in his head anymore. It was just noise.

---

The house in Bagbazar had a large wooden door that had swollen from the monsoon damp, refusing to open more than a foot. Vikram had to shoulder it twice, the old iron lock cracking inside the wood with a sharp sound like dry bone breaking.

The air inside the house was thick and heavy. It smelled of bat droppings, wet lime, and the cold, unventilated damp of twenty years of shadow. 

The plaster had fallen off the walls in large, curved sheets, showing the thin red bricks underneath. A courtyard sat in the middle, three neem trees growing wild, their thick roots lifting the old stone tiles at strange angles. 

An old marble nameplate near the entrance read: *Sen family. 1924.*

Ananya walked in first, her plastic sandals making clean prints in the thick grey dust that covered the stone floor. "It has many rooms," she said, looking up.

"Eleven," Sarita said, leaning against the door frame to catch her breath. She looked at the courtyard, at the dry neem leaves that had piled up in the corners. "The tap is in the corner," she said, pointing to a rusted iron pipe rising from the stone floor.

Vikram went to the tap. He turned the heavy brass handle. 

A dry squeak echoed through the courtyard. Then, a thin stream of orange, rust-stained water came out, sputtering before it went clear and cold. 

He drew a handful. It tasted of iron and river sand. 

He washed his face. The water felt different from the Odisha well. It was heavier, older.

Sarita sat on the lowest step of the verandah, her head resting against the wooden pillar that had been eaten away by termites near the base. "We will start with the front room," she said. "Sweep the dust. The patients are waiting at the crossing with the luggage."

Vikram picked up a broom he had bought at the station. The bamboo bristles were stiff, scratching the old stone floor with a sharp, dry sound. 

Ananya sat near the well tap, setting her three-legged horse on a clean stone she had wiped with her skirt. It stood.

"See?" she said, pointing. "It works here too."

Vikram began to sweep. The dust rose in the afternoon sun, turning the shafts of light into columns of moving, grey sand. 

He swept the first room, then the second. His hands, already hard from the well rope of Odisha, didn't feel the rough bamboo handle anymore. 

He had left the boardrooms. He had left the big white cars. He had left the name that opened gates. 

But as he swept the dust of twenty years out of the Sen family house, the iron-tasting water of the Bagbazar tap felt like exactly enough to keep him where he was.

[End of Part 1]
